samples representing each forecast lead time and a month/season of the year. To gain insights on how increasing the length of training record and using diÔ¨Äerent seasonal windows for training can aÔ¨Äect the predictions of benchmark models, we train each model with diÔ¨Äerent training window sizes and regulations. A summary of training schemes for ANNCSGD and benchmark models is provided as follows:
‚Ä¢ UniÔ¨Åed approach (ANN-CSGD) uses forecast-observation pairs of all months and lead times of training years for training and hyperparameter tuning, resulting in a training sample size of up to 7 lead times √ó 28 years √ó 365 days = 71540, 20% of which is dedicated for hyperparameter tuning and not used in training.

‚Ä¢ MMGD and CSGD with 61 days and 91 days training windows (MMGD-61, CSGD-61) and (MMGD-91, CSGD-91) use 61 and 91 training days around the 15th of each month across training years for generating PQPF for out of sample data of that month, yielding training sample size up to 28 years √ó 61 days = 1708 and 28 years √ó 91 days = 2548 for each lead time and month, respectively. 61 days and 91 days training windows have been used in several past studies (e.g., Hamill et al., 2015; Scheuerer and Hamill, 2015, Scheuerer and Hamill, 2018; Scheuerer et al., 2017; Wu et al., 2018).
‚Ä¢ MMGD seasonal training scheme (MMGD-seasonal), where forecasts in out of sample data from the cool (October-April) and dry (May-

