(A6)

D. Reliability diagrams and sharpness histograms

The reliability and resolution of a probabilistic forecast for exceeding some speciÔ¨Åc thresholds (ùúè) can be assessed graphically using reliability diagrams. The reliability diagram consists of a plot of the average

12

M. Ghazvinian, Y. Zhang, D.-J. Seo et al.

Advances in Water Resources 151 (2021) 103907

values of forecast probabilities exceeding ùúè, against that of observed relative frequencies over each deÔ¨Åned probability category. In a reliable probabilistic forecast, the reliability diagram should be close to 1:1 line. Interested readers are referred to Brocker and Smith (2007) and Wilks (2011) for details on how to interpret the deÔ¨Åciencies in probabilistic forecasts using reliability diagrams. To assess the sharpness of PQPF for speciÔ¨Åc thresholds, we use sharpness histograms to investigate the frequency of forecast probabilities for diÔ¨Äerent probability bins. Note, a sharp forecast is characterized by higher frequencies for the forecast probabilities close to either 0 or 1.

E. The Diebold-Mariano test

To assess statistical signiÔ¨Åcance of veriÔ¨Åcation score diÔ¨Äerences be-

tween two forecast methods, we use the Diebold-Mariano statistical test

of the null hypothesis of equal predictive performance (Diebold and

Mariano, 1995). Let Œî = SF1 ‚àí SF2 denote the vector of veriÔ¨Åcation score

S diÔ¨Äerences from two competing iÔ¨Åcation sample with length n, Œî

=for1e‚àïcùëõa‚àëst ùëõùëñm=1eŒîthùëñ ,oadnsdF1ùúéÃÇ ŒîanadsFu2itaobvleer

veresti-

mator of asymptotic conditions, the test

ssttaatnidstaircdùë°ùëõde=vi‚àöatùëõioùúéÃÇŒîÃÑnŒî

of Œî. Under standard regularity asymptotically follows a stan-

dard Gaussian distribution under the null hypothesis of no diÔ¨Äerence in

predictive performances of two competing forecast methods. Following

the past studies (Baran and Lerch, 2016, 2018; Rasp and Lerch, 2018) ùúéÃÇŒî can be estimated by square root of sample autocovariance up to lag k ‚àí 1

for the k step-ahead forecasts to account for temporal dependencies in

forecast errors. We use one-sided Diebold-Mariano tests. The alternative

hypothesis is that forecast method F2 underperforms forecast method F1 and the statistical signiÔ¨Åcancy of the test‚Äôs statistic can be assessed by

obtaining corresponding p-value. we perform the tests based on both

CRPS and squared error of mean PQPF (on a limited basis) and for each

lead time and separately for each river basin. To address spatial depen-

dence of forecast errors, scores are averaged across sub-basins in each

river basins (M. Scheuerer 2021, personal communication). Further, we

adjust the test results by accounting for test multiplicity (i.e., simultane-

ously analyzing test results of multiple lead times) using false discovery

rate (FDR) method (Benjamini and Hochberg, 1995) by controlling the

FDR at the level ùõºFDR = 0.05. Note that, this procedure was discussed by Wilks (2016) in spatial context where test results are interpreted si-

multaneously across multiple grid points but also was suggested to be

applied whenever the results of simultaneous several hypothesis tests

are reported or interpreted.

